article.headline: Oregon State 70, Prairie View 53
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Oregon State coach Jay John admits his starting lineup "may be an issue every game." The Beavers returned only one starter this season, Lamar Hurd, but beat Prairie View A&M 70-53 in the opener Saturday night for both teams. David Lucas led the Beavers with 16 points. The Beavers feature no seniors on their roster for the first time since the 1978-79 season. John's starting lineup consisted of freshman Kenny Hooks and beefed-up junior Lucas at the forwards with Hurd and Nash in the backcourt along with promising freshman Kyle Jeffers at center. "We're still aren't capable of playing a 40 minute game. It may take a month or six weeks, I thought we came with good effort tonight, but we're pleased to be 1-0 this year," John said. Oregon State jumped on the Panthers early with a 15-4 opening spurt and led by as many as 21 never relinquishing the lead all night despite a surge by the Panthers which saw the deficit cut to seven points three times. OSU led 35-22 halftime on the strength of their defense which held Prairie View to just 9-of-27 shooting from the field. For the game, the Beavers shot 43 percent (26-61) from the field. "We are trying to push the ball, and when we have leads we are trying to execute certain things," John said. "I can only seem to get four people on the same page at the pace that it needs to be. That's something we need to try and improve." Angelo Tsagarakis was 3-for-4 from 3-point range and wound up with 10 points and Jim Hanchett had eight points and grabbed eight rebounds in their Oregon State debuts. The Panthers had 25 turnovers and were held by the Beavers to 33 percent shooting for the game. "We've got to able to play defense, and have some control of the game," John said. "Our defense certainly created some offense tonight." The Panthers were led by impressive 6-foot-10 freshman forward Tyrone Nelson who had a game-high 22 points and 13 rebounds. OSU has now won seven of its last eight season openers, all at home, and 12 of its last 13 non-conference home games, including the last five. The Beavers next face the University of Portland on Tuesday in Corvallis.
